  "response_text": "Speed and velocity are both measures of how fast an object is moving, but they have distinct differences:\n\n1. **Speed**:\n   - Speed is a scalar quantity, which means it only has magnitude (size or amount) without any direction.\n   - It is defined as the rate at which an object covers distance. Mathematically, speed is calculated as the total distance traveled divided by the time taken to travel that distance.\n   - For example, if a car travels 100 kilometers in 2 hours, its average speed is 50 kilometers per hour.\n\n2. **Velocity**:\n   - Velocity is a vector quantity, meaning it has both magnitude and direction.\n   - It is defined as the rate of change of position with respect to time. In other words, it describes not just how fast an object is moving but also in what direction.\n   - For example, if the same car is traveling 100 kilometers north in 2 hours, its average velocity",
